    {
      "id": "mpi-is-07f6afa9068b",
      "title": "The fastest and smallest suction feeder is a carnivorous pant – how to operate near suction feeding’s hydrodynamic limit",
      "speaker": "Ulrike Müller, Fresno State University",
      "abstract": "Among carnivorous plants, bladderworts stand out by having the smallest and fastest traps, completing capture events within just a few milliseconds. Their underwater milli-meter sized suction traps are hollow bladders sealed by a door. The traps are loaded by removing water from the bladder lumen, generating a sub-ambient pressure inside the trap and elastically loading the trap walls. Suction events are triggered when prey touch trigger hairs at the trap door, which causes the door to open and the prey to be sucked in. Bladderwort traps generate flow accelerations and peak speeds that far exceed values observed in similarly sized animal suction feeders and require considerably more power. Due to their small size, bladderwort traps operate in a flow regime in which suction power and ene... Janneke Schwaner",
